[30;1m270 | [0m[35mDue to a bug of sorts in our SSH layer, it's not currently possible for Fabric[0m
[30;1m271 | [0m[35mto always accurately detect the type of authentication needed. We have to try[0m
[30;1m272 | [0m[35mand guess whether we're being asked for a private key passphrase or a remote[0m
[30;1m273 | [0m[35mserver password, and in some cases our guess ends up being wrong.[0m

[30;1m275 | [0m[35mThe most common such situation is where you, the local user, appear to have an[0m
[30;1m276 | [0m[35mSSH keychain agent running, but the remote server is not able to honor your SSH[0m

[30;1m407 | [0m[35mThis is also how you can tell Fabric to run on multiple remote systems at once:[0m
[30;1m408 | [0m[35mbecause ``env.hosts`` is a list, ``fab`` iterates over it, calling the given[0m
[30;1m409 | [0m[35mtask once for each connection.[0m
[30;1m410 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m2 | [0m[35mSSH behavior[0m
[30;1m3 | [0m[35m============[0m
[30;1m4 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35mFabric currently makes use of a pure-Python SSH re-implementation for managing[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mconnections, meaning that there are occasionally spots where it is limited by[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35mthat library's capabilities. Below are areas of note where Fabric will exhibit[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mbehavior that isn't consistent with, or as flexible as, the behavior of the[0m

[30;1m85 | [0m[35mstrings specifying a username, hostname and port combination, in the form of[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35m``username@hostname:port``. User and/or port (and the associated ``@`` or[0m
